  "summary": "Robin Upward greets Ariadne Mrs. Oliver at Golden Chain Manor, discussing his ideas for a second act of a play. He assists Mrs. Oliver with her luggage and invites her and Hercule Poirot inside to meet his mother, Laura Upward. Laura, an invalid in her sixties who uses a wheelchair, welcomes them into a luxurious living room.\n\nDuring the visit, Mrs. Oliver explains that Poirot is investigating the murder of Mrs. McGinty, a cleaning lady who worked at the manor the previous autumn. Robin expresses disappointment that the case is not a secret, while Mrs. Oliver notes that the wrong man was convicted and faces execution unless the real murderer is found. Robin describes the deceased cleaning lady as a very proper and tidy person. Laura Upward mentions her reliance on a faithful maid for simple cooking and expresses her dislike of needing to rely on others as her health declines.\n\nAfter the social call, Poirot departs to catch a train to Gillingham to meet Superintendent Spence. As he leaves, he hears Robin making disparaging remarks about Poirot's appearance. While walking, Poirot narrowly avoids being hit by a van driven by Samson. Poirot then visits the modern home of the Carringtons, the residence of Guy Carrington, a wealthy engineer and aspiring politician. A butler refuses to let Poirot in, claiming the Carringtons are out, but Poirot encounters a young woman in a fur coat who identifies herself as Mrs. Carpenter. She remains cool and indifferent to Poirot's identity.",
